Angmering, Sussex, England":"Angmering, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Steyning, Sussex, England":"Steyning, Sussex, England"},"en":{"1318–1371":"1318–1371","1317–1380":"1317–1380","1339–1380":"1339–1380","1285–1345":"1285–1345","1289–Female":"1289–Deceased","1285":"1285","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1337":"1337","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","about 1339":"1339","1289":"1289","1453":"1453","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1339":"1339","1317":"1317","Angmering, Sussex, England":"Angmering, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Steyning, Sussex, England":"Steyning, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Palmer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>palmer(e)</i> ‘palmer, pilgrim to the Holy Land’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>palmer</i>, Old French <i>pa(l)mer</i>, <i>paum(i)er</i>), so called from the palm branch carried by such pilgrims. The term was also used to denote an itinerant monk who traveled from shrine to shrine under a vow of poverty. This surname is also common in Ireland, where it has been recorded from the 13th century onward.","Irish: when not of English origin (see 1 above), a surname adopted for Gaelic <b>Ó Maolfhoghmhair</b> (see   Milford  ), the name of an ecclesiastical family.","Swedish (mainly <b>Palmér</b>): ornamental name formed with <i>palm</i> ‘palm tree’ + the suffix <i>-ér</i> (a derivative of Latin <i>-erius</i>) or <i>-er</i> (from German)."],"variants":[{"name":"Milford","meanings":["English (mainly Devon): habitational name from any of the many places called Milford, deriving from Old English <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","Irish (Antrim and Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maolfhoghmhair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Maolgfhoghmhair</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘chief of harvest’. The Irish name was first Anglicized as <b>Mullover</b>, which was later assimilated to <i>Milford</i>. See also   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Palmiere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Dante, Enrico, Nicola, Salvatore, Vittorio.","Italian: from <i>palmiere</i> ‘palmer, pilgrim’. See   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Parmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Palmer  .","Indian (northern states): variant of   Parmar  ."]},{"name":"Palmore","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Palmer   or an Americanized form of South German   Balmer  ."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":10,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":19,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Adam Palmer was born in 1318, in Steyning, Sussex, England, his father, John Palmer, was 34 and his mother, Miss Pelham, was 30. He married Lady Mary Isabella Seddinghouse, Baroness Palmer in 1333, in Angmering, Sussex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1371, in Sussex, England, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1318–1371":"1318–1371","1317–1380":"1317–1380","1339–1380":"1339–1380","1285–1345":"1285–1345","1289–Female":"1289–Surnud","1285":"1285","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1337":"1337","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","about 1339":"1339","1289":"1289","1453":"1453","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1339":"1339","1317":"1317","Angmering, Sussex, England":"Angmering, Sus